{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493105"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:56:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:56:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1225"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1225"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.16,0.04,0.7,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1225"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90523"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1225"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1225"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74763"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"673"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2778"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31051"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90523"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents with a three-week history of abdominal fullness. He has otherwise been well. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he appears well. His pulse rate is 62/min and blood pressure 120/70mmHg. On abdominal examination the only abnormal finding is a smooth-surfaced, non-tender mass in the left upper quadrant on abdominal palpation. It extends eight cm below the left costal margin and toward the midline. The mass moves with respiration and is dull to percussion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydatid disease","Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Adrenal neoplasm","Splenic cyst","Renal tumour"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe physical examination reveals a mass in the left upper quadrant, which could be related to the spleen or the stomach. Its movement with respiration is most suggestive of an enlarged spleen. A \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrointestinal stromal tumour\u003C/strong\u003E is a reasonable differential, as it can present with vague and non-specific symptoms such as abdominal fullness. However, it would be uncommon in an individuals of this age. In addition, such tumours usually have a heterogenous appearance on CT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenic cyst\u003C/strong\u003E may be parasitic or non-parasitic. As the spleen sits right below the left hemidiaphragm, it is more likely to move with respiration. This is the most likely diagnosis. Splenic cysts are usually incidental findings, but cysts of this size may well produce symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe kidneys are retroperitoneal structures, meaning a \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal tumour \u003C/strong\u003Eor \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenal neoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E would not cross the midline. It would also be rare for either of these to reach this size without involving other symptoms. In addition, the mass in this patient moves with respiration, meaning it is unlikely to be of retroperitoneal origin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydatid disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a cystic disease of the liver secondary to parasitic infection. As such it would present with a right upper quadrant mass. However, in getting to this size, the lesion would have been present for several, if not many, years and would have a calcified rim.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An abdominal mass crossing the midline must be peritoneal rather than retroperitoneal."],"references":["Morgenstern L. Nonparasitic splenic cysts: pathogenesis, classification, and treatment. J Am Coll Surg. 2002;194. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11893134/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74763"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1225"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1532"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1532"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9edbbfdf-f70e-4aa4-b6d2-a45a039191d4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9edbbfdf-f70e-4aa4-b6d2-a45a039191d4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":725,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74763"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T10:27:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T10:27:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1225"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90523"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups